                         CHOOSING YOUR VIDEO SOURCE

    Take a look at your video camera, camcorder or video recorder`s video
out socket and using a suitable cable, plug it into the Vidi-Amiga 12`s
Phono socket.
    there are many different makes of video cameras, etc. on the market, but
there are only three common types of composite video sockets!

    The first and by far the most common is the phono connector, shown
opposite.
    This will be labelled Composite Video Out or Video Out.
    Consult your video machines manual.
    We supply with the Vidi-Amiga 12 a  phono plug to Phono plug cable for
connecting straight to this type of socket.
    The second type is the multi pin SCART socket like the one in this
picture.

PAGE 6

    Most video or television shops can supply you with a Scart plug - Phono
plug cable.
    But we can supply our own Scart Plug adaptor which has a Phono socket on
it as an extra if required.

    The last and rarest is the BNC socket. This is usually found on more
expensive video recorders and again Rombo can supply a BNC plug - Phono plug
adapter if necessary.

    If you do have a machine which uses a different type of video connector,
then a special case may have to be purchased from your video dealer.

    Owners of S-VHS or Hi8 machines may use the higher picture quality S-VHS
input, a suitable cable may be obtained from video dealers.

    PLEASE NOTE THAT ANY SOCKET LABELLED RF OUTPUT OR TELEVISION OUTPUT MUST
NOT BE USED, AS THIS TYPE OF CONNECTOR IS TOTALLY UNSUITABLE FOR THE VID1
AMIGA 12.

    This is a picture of a typical RF OUTPUT or ANT OUT socket.

PAGE 7

    Once you have decided on which video source you are using either
composite video (Phono, SCART or BNC) or S-Video (S-VHS, Hi8), connect the
appropriate cable from the video source to the Vidi Amiga 12.
    (Please note that only one source can be connected to the Vidi Amiga 12
at any one time).
    If you what to grab an image from a camera, then the best setup is to
position the camera directly over the object and have a strong  (preferably
daylight) light source at an angle of 45 degs to the object. This prevents
the light source from reflecting off the object into the camera lens.

                     GRABBING YOUR  FIRST COLOUR IMAGE

                           ***** SEE PIC 2 ******

    From the Vidi Amiga 12 MAIN CONTROL PANEL, click on the grab gadget.
    The MAIN CONTROL PANEL will be replaced with a GRABBER CONTROL PANEL at
the bottom of the screen and in the background will be a constantly updating
black and white image of the video source.
    If you get the message "No Video Signal found" then either the video
source is not connected correctly or the video source is switched off!
    You can now adjust your video source's focus or brightness if you wish
or by using the two left most vertical sliders on the GRABBER CONTROL PANEL
make minor adjustments to the black and white levels.

PAGE 8

    Once you are happy with the image displayed, click on the GRAB gadget
and a MIXING FRAMES window will appear. after a period of time, a full
screen picture will be displayed. To return to the GRABBER CONTROL PANEL
simply click on the colour picture with the left mouse button.

    You will notice that a white tick has appeared next to the colour
button, this indicates that a colour image is stored. to view the picture
again click on the VIEW gadget.
    To return to the panel click on the picture again with the left mouse
button.

    Please note that for the best quality colour images, the image you are
trying to grab must be absolutely still for approximately one second after you
have clicked the GRAB gadget.

    Note: Even expensive video machines using so called still or pause
picture can in fact be slightly jumping, and this can affect the quality of
the colour image. Only video machines with a digital freeze frame can be
said to be perfectly still.

    After the initial view you may want to adjust the amount of colour
present, this is set by the third vertical slider from the left. You will
need to repeatedly click on the GRAB gadget and then re-adjust the colour
bar until you are satisfied with the picture.

    The grabbed image is only temporarily stored in the Grab Frame buffer in
the Vidi Amiga 12 and if you were to grab another colour image the previous
one will be lost.

PAGE 9

    To store the image in the computer you need to click on STORE. This will
transfer the picture to the CAROUSEL part of the software and you will
notice that a white tick (along with red, green and blue) will disappear.
    This indicates that there is no colour image to view from the GRABBER
CONTROL PANEL and you may safely grab another image.

                          MIXING YOUR COLOUR IMAGE

    When you grabbed a colour image, the Vidi Amiga 12 took three pictures
(a red, green and blue picture) of the image and placed them in a temporary
buffer. These three images are known as RGB triple. You can see that they
are stored by the three red, green and blue ticks highlighted in the GRABBER
CONTROL PANEL.
    The Vidi Amiga 12 software requires these separate images to remix them
into a new image.

    Clicking on the MIX gadget on the left side of the GRABBER CONTROL PANEL
allows the COLOUR MIXING PREFERENCES PANEL to open and allow you to select
different scree modes and resolutions. as shown below.

                           ***** SEE PIC 2 *****

PAGE 10

    You should see that HAM has been selected and the screen resolution is
set to 320*256 (320*200 in America). Click repeatedly on the HAM gadget
until 16 colours is shown and click on the ERROR DIFFUSION gadget as this
will improve the mixed picture quality. Finally click on the MIX gadget in
the MIXING PREFERENCES PANEL and the MIXING FRAMES bar will appear, after a
short time it will have finished processing the new image. To see the
results of your mix, click on the VIEW gadget on the GRABBER CONTROL PANEL.

    You can repeat this and select other screen modes and resolutions, but
please remember not all Amigas can display all the various combinations and
the message IMAGE DISPLAY MODE IS NOT AVAILABLE ON THIS AMIGA that may pop up
instead of your image means that your particular Amiga can not display that
type of picture, but you will still be able to save the picture to disc if
you wish. See page 20 for a list of the screen modes which you can display
in.

